title="Principles of Mathematical Analysis">Principles of Mathematical Analysis</fr:link>, Appendix to Ch. 1</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We then define the multiplication for <fr:em>any arbitrary</fr:em> <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-000U.xml"
addr="ca-000U"
title="Dedekind cuts">Dedekind cuts</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \in  R]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta \in  R]]></fr:tex> by
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\alpha \beta  = \begin {cases}(-\alpha )(-\beta ) & \hbox {if }\alpha <0_{R},\beta <0_{R},\\ -[(-\alpha )\beta ] & \hbox {if }\alpha <0_{R}<\beta \\ -[\alpha \cdot (-\beta )] & \hbox {if }\beta <0_{R}<\alpha . \end {cases}]]></fr:tex>
The product used in each of these cases is the one from <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-000Y.xml"
addr="ca-000Y"
title="Addition of Dedekind cuts satisfies the relevant ordered field axioms">Addition of Dedekind cuts satisfies the relevant ordered field axioms</fr:link>.</fr:p><fr:p>Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma =-(-\gamma )]]></fr:tex>, the axioms for multiplication of a <fr:link
type="local"
href="field-0001.xml"
addr="field-0001"
title="Field">Field</fr:link> holds for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> except we need to check distributivity.</fr:p><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ,\beta ,\gamma \in  R]]></fr:tex>. Then
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\alpha (\beta +\gamma )=\alpha \beta +\alpha \gamma .]]></fr:tex>
The proof breaks up into cases depending on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha >0_{R}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha <0_{R}]]></fr:tex>, and separately <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta >0_{R}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta <0_{R}]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta +\gamma >0_{R}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta +\gamma <0_{R}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>For example, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha >0_{R}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta <0_{R}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta +\gamma >0_{R}]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma =(\beta +\gamma )+(-\beta )]]></fr:tex>, which means
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\alpha \gamma =\alpha (\beta +\gamma )+\alpha \cdot (-\beta )]]></fr:tex>
But <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \cdot (-\beta )=-(\alpha \beta )]]></fr:tex>. Thus
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\alpha \beta +\alpha \gamma =\alpha (\beta +\gamma ).]]></fr:tex>
The remaining cases are proved similarly.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
