title="Principles of Mathematical Analysis">Principles of Mathematical Analysis</fr:link>, Appendix to Ch. 1</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We claim the set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> of Dedekind cuts has the <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-0007.xml"
addr="ca-0007"
title="Least-Upper-Bound Property">Least-Upper-Bound Property</fr:link>.</fr:p><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> be a nonempty subset of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>, assume <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta \in  R]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-0004.xml"
addr="ca-0004"
title="Upper bound, bounded above">upper bound</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>Now, set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma  = \bigcup  A]]></fr:tex> the union of all elements of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>. We claim that (1) <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma ]]></fr:tex> is a Dedekind cut and (2) <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma =\sup (A)]]></fr:tex>. The result follows from these two claims.</fr:p><fr:p><fr:strong>Claim 1:</fr:strong> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma ]]></fr:tex> is a Dedekind cut. There are three criteria we need to prove:</fr:p><fr:p>(I) <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma ]]></fr:tex> is not empty and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma \neq \mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is not empty, there is some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{0}\in  A]]></fr:tex> which means it is a proper subset <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{0}\subset \gamma ]]></fr:tex>. This means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma ]]></fr:tex> is not empty.</fr:p><fr:p>Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta ]]></fr:tex> is an upper bound of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, this means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma \subset \beta ]]></fr:tex>. Therefore <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma \neq \mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>. This establishes the first property.</fr:p><fr:p>(II) If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in \gamma ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[q\in \mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[q<p]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[q\in \gamma ]]></fr:tex>. There is some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{1}\in  A]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in \alpha _{1}]]></fr:tex>. If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[q<p]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[q\in \alpha _{1}]]></fr:tex>, which implies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[q\in \gamma ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>(III) If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in \gamma ]]></fr:tex>, then there exists an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r\in \gamma ]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p<r]]></fr:tex>. If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in \gamma ]]></fr:tex>, then there exists an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{1}\in  A]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in \alpha _{1}]]></fr:tex>. If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r\in \alpha _{1}]]></fr:tex> is chosen such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r>p]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r\in \gamma ]]></fr:tex> since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{1}\subset \gamma ]]></fr:tex>. This proves (III).</fr:p><fr:p>Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma ]]></fr:tex> is a Dedekind cut.</fr:p><fr:p><fr:strong>Claim 2:</fr:strong> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma =\sup (A)]]></fr:tex>. For any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta <\gamma ]]></fr:tex>, there is an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[s\in \gamma ]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[s\notin \delta ]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[s\in \gamma ]]></fr:tex>, there is some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[s\in \alpha ]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta <\alpha ]]></fr:tex> which means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta ]]></fr:tex> is not an upper bound of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
